Q1:
Welcome! The purpose of this research project is to explore the voting patterns of undergraduate students at the University of California Berkeley. This is a research project being conducted by Hannah Hill, a senior Peace and Conflict Studies major, at the University of California Berkeley. Your responses will contribute to the understanding of youth voter turnout and what factors influence youth to participate in voting.
The procedure involves filling out an online survey that will take approximately 10-13 minutes. 
PARTICIPATIONIf you decide to participate in this research survey, you have the right to withdraw at any time. You may choose not to participate. If you decide not to participate in this study or if you withdraw from participating at any time, you will not be penalized. While most of the questions are generally about voting and registration, there may be a few questions that might cause you discomfort.
CONFIDENTIALITYThe results of this study will be used for scholarly purposes only and may be shared with the University of California Berkeley representatives. Your responses will be kept confidential and no identifying information such as your name, email address or IP address will be collected.If you have any questions about the research study, please contact Dr. Crystal Chang at crystalchang@berkeley.edu.
ELECTRONIC CONSENT
Clicking on the "I consent" button below indicates that: 

• You have read the above information.
• You voluntarily agree to participate.
• You are at least 18 years of age. • You are an American citizen.• You are currently a full-time UC Berkeley undergraduate student.

Q32_1_TEXT: Physically going to a polling station is more exciting and it connects me to the larger feeling that my vote will have an impact. Taking the time out of my day also makes me think more about why I'm voting and its significance. Mailing in a ballot doesn't have the same exciting as putting each page into the voting machine and seeing other people exercising their right to vote.
Q33_1_TEXT: I wouldn't say that there was one specific event, but Trump's entire presidency and what has come with that - increase in hate crimes, horrible rhetoric surrounding immigration, islamaphobia, homophobia, limitation of the press, etc (I could go on for days). I also felt a responsibility, as a white woman, to vote this year considering white women are going to be the death of this country based off of how they have voted during these midterms and the 2016 elections.
Q37: I do not have a job
Q45_3_TEXT: I kind of listed a lot of reason in another question, but I'll make this one more personal. Trump has made, at least within my household, certain topics political that never were before. My parents are extremely fiscally conservative, but socially liberal (I know that isn't really possible, but I'm trying to give my parents the benefit of the doubt). Before Trump, we could talk about racism, homophobia, women's rights, etc without an argument because those things were not political. They connected to our morals and values they had instilled in me and we agreed on those issues; however, because of Trump, these topics have been politicized and conflated with party loyalty. Now when I bring up racism in relation to Trump's rhetoric, I am labeled a "radical" in my household and "brainwashed" by Cal. Before these were moral issues, not they are party issues, which has put a huge strain on my relationship with my parents. My parents did not vote for Obama because of his economic plans, but they supported the unity he brought to the U.S. and hope having a Black president brought to different communities. Now, they think Trump is crazy, but he has rubbed off on them. They believe in the Fake News rhetoric and the sensitivity of "snowflake" democrats. So... Fuck Trump and fuck what he did to my parents. Oh also, fuck Trump for being a fake Christian. He used religious rhetoric to get voters but is not religious himself. Half my family votes for him cause he's religious and one day when my aunts yell at me for "using the Lord's name in vain" I'm gonna backhandedly slap them and say "Your evil satanic President using the Lord's name in vain to get your white female vote"
Q46_3_TEXT: While the economy is doing better and unemployment is down, the money saved by large companies has not trickled down to employees so no I don't support the Tax reform. I would describe basically all policies and reforms as fake as fuck. Trump and the Republican party have chosen a huge population of the U.S, the working class, as their voting pawns while they literally stab them in the back with their reforms. Don't even get me started on climate change stuff and his support for the coal industry. I wish we could press charges against Trump for killing Mother Nature.
Q49: Presidential elections and midterm elections are equally as important
Q50_1_TEXT: Most recently I have attended multiple Union strikes and protests in the Bay area. One at Cal and a couple at Kaiser and the Marriott Hotels. (I intern for a Union and am really into the labor movement). I went to anti-trump and anti-the "free speech week" protests as well. I also attended the Women's March two years ago, but have skipped it the last two because it caters so much to white women and ignores those marginalized farrrrrrr beyond us. That's not to say those that go to that are bad at all. I still support it! I just try to support it in other ways than attending.
Q52_1_TEXT: Hope your thesis research and writing is going well! Writing a thesis is stressful stuff on top of everything else you're probably doing at Cal, so props to you for taking this on. I hope I can read it when you're done. Sofie Fier sent this form to me so you can thank her for my kind of whacky responses... Sorry if I went too "off" on some of the questions. If you have any follow up questions, I'd love to help in any way. If you're feeling bogged down by work and the semester, just remember that what you're doing is important and significant and that you're at Cal for a reason. You rock!
